, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Roger","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French personal name, <i>Rog(i)er</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, from <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>gār</i>, <i>gēr</i> ‘spear’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain, replacing the native Old English form <i>Hrōðgār</i>. <i>Roger</i> was one of the most popular boys' names throughout the medieval period, but less so after the Reformation, though it has continued in regular use to the present day.  Roger, Count of Sicily  (  <i>c.</i>1031–1101 ), son of Tancred, recovered Sicily from the Arabs. His son, also called Roger, ruled Sicily as king, presiding over a court noted for its splendour and patronage of the arts."],"variants":[{"name":"Rodger","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Roger  , in part from the surname derived from the given name in the Middle Ages."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Roger de Wickersley was born in 1420, in Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Richard FitzTurgis DeWickersley, was 38 and his mother, Agnis Fitz Turgis de Wickersley, was 20. He married Joanna de la Roche about 1450, in England. They were the parents of at least 2 daughters. He died on 24 May 1471, in his hometown, at the age of 51."},"et":{"1420–24 May 1471":"1420–24. mai 1471","1420–1471":"1420–1471","1425–1472":"1425–1472","1450–1526":"1450–1526","1452–Female":"1452–Surnud","1382–Male":"1382–Surnud","1400–Female":"1400–Surnud","1425":"1425","1400":"1400","1420":"1420","1452":"1452","1450":"1450","24 May 1471":"24. mai 1471","1472":"1472","1471":"1471","1382":"1382","about 1452":"umbes 1452","about 1450":"umbes 1450","1526":"1526","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"England","Bolton Percy, Yorkshire, England":"Bolton Percy, Yorkshire, England"},"fi":{"1420–24 May 1471":"1420